<TEXT>
when she was born beth coles doctors said 
she would never be able to walk but the 14yearold high school 
freshman has overcome congenital bone defects and is now a 
cheerleader 
after enduring years of operations including amputation of both 
feet she attends wynford high school royals basketball games 
wearing artificial limbs that fit over the calf up to the knee 
my parents and god have helped me she said before dashing 
onto the court at a recent basketball game 
she has the guts and potential that are godgiven said her 
father william we take very little credit shes done it on her 
own 
at birth beths hips were dislocated and the bones in her legs 
werent formed doctors said she would never walk 
at three months doctors wrapped her body in a full cast hoping 
to straighten her hips she wore the cast until she was 11 months 
old 
after hundreds of treatments by specialists at shriners hospital 
for crippled children in chicago she finally decided at age 10 to 
undergo amputation instead of bone fusion 
after the first amputation she walked into her fourthgrade 
classroom on the first day of school with a prosthesis on her right 
leg and a pair of crutches 
she underwent the second amputation in june 1988 but only after 
playing for the seventhgrade girls volleyball team and trying out 
for cheerleading 
</TEXT>
