<DOCNO> AP891211-0002 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
more than a halfcentury after 
fleeing the nazis 81yearold nina rubinstein on monday received 
her doctorate in sociology at frankfurt university 
its the last thing i expected in my life said miss 
rubinstein of new york im elated im proud im surprised 
the dean of frankfurts johann wolfgang goethe universitys 
sociology department lothar brock said miss rubinstein was 
awarded the degree magna cum laude 
it was a big surprise for the retired united nations 
interpreter who was 25 when she fled the nazis in 1933 leaving 
behind her completed 247page thesis for her doctorate 
she first fled to france and then to the united states when 
hitlers troops marched on france 
im not particularly proud of myself in general but i thought 
the dissertation was rather good miss rubinstein said it was 
delivered in german 
but frankly i did not expect a magna cum laude that was a 
very enormous surprise she said chuckling 
miss rubinstein arrived in west germany last week to take part 
in a colloquium friday part of 75th anniversary celebrations at 
the universtiys social sciences department 
im absolutely shattered i think i never have been so 
exhausted not only physically but psychologically too after that 
day on friday the softspoken miss rubinstein said 
as part of the colloquium miss rubinstein read several poems 
taking an active part in the ceremonies said professor david 
kettler who was instrumental in arranging for her to get the 
degree 
kettler of trent university in peterborough ontario said it 
took him a year along with miss rubinsteins halfsister hanna 
papanek to make arrangements for awarding the doctorate 
it was like one of those ideas you suddenly have in the 
shower kettler said this is the university facing up to its 
responsibility to its students and faculty she did the work and 
deserves to be recognized for it 
miss rubinstein was born in berlin in 1908 to parents of jewish 
descent who fled their native latvia as political exiles after the 
failed russian revolution of 1905 
she lived in neutral denmark from 1914 through 1917 where she 
had fled with her mother to avoid world war i 
later she returned to germany to study and in 1928 began 
working toward her degree under the noted sociology professor karl 
mannheim 
miss rubinstein recalled how she enjoyed being in mannheims 
presence and how the students used to meet him at cafe laumer in 
the university area of frankfurts bockenheim district 
we very often met there with mannheim of course all the 
young ladies there adored him he was extremely attractive ive 
never forgotten that she said 
miss rubinstein then pointed out photographs showing herself 
and other students reading and chatting at the cafe with mannheim 
taken between 1930 and 1933 
he went to england right away after the nazis came miss 
rubinstein said i never saw him again i lost contact with him 
mannheim who last worked at the london school of economics had 
published dozens of manuscripts on sociology including man and 
society in an age of reconstruction in 1935 he died in england 
in 1947 
miss rubinstein said she was ready to defend her thesis titled 
the french emigration after 1789 a contribution to the 
sociology of political emigration when the nazis took over 
frankfurt university in 1933 
she said a nazi student retrieved her thesis which she left 
behind on a desk in the university before she fled to paris 
in paris she worked as a translator and secretary for a literary 
agency but fled again in 1940 when the nazis invaded france 
leaving everything behind including her thesis 
a french neighbor kept miss rubinsteins belongings and after 
the war traced her to new york and sent the thesis to her she said 
miss rubinstein who worked as a simultaneous translator 
mostly in russian for the united nations shelved the thesis 
for years until her halfsister ms papanek a research professor 
of anthropology at boston university began trying to get it 
published 
later efforts by ms papanek kettler and frankfurt 
universitys brock and professor claudia honegger arranged for 
miss rubinstein to finally receive her degree 
miss rubinstein said she will return to new york thursday 
im incredibly tired and i have the feeling when i come back 
to new york im going to go to bed and stay there for a couple of 
days she said 
</TEXT>
