<TEXT>
in a decision narrowing the reach of the 
freedom of information act the supreme court today shielded the 
fbi from having to give grumman corp documents received from 
another government agency 
by a 63 vote the court said the documents can be withheld 
because they were compiled for law enforcement purposes and 
therefore are exempt from the 1966 law aimed at curtailing 
government secrecy 
grumman and the defense contract audit agency exchanged letters 
in 1978 in the exchange the pentagon agency questioned certain 
accounting practices grumman used for defense contracts grumman 
defended its practices and no government action was taken 
the fbi began a criminal investigation of grumman in 1985 and 
the exchange of letters was sent from the audit agency to the fbi 
grumman filed an foia lawsuit in 1987 seeking all documents 
that are related in any way to the subject of the 1978 
correspondence 
a federal judge ruled against the contractor saying release of 
the documents would jeopardize a grand jury investigation 
but the 2nd us circuit court of appeals in new york city ruled 
that the foia requires release of the documents 
the appeals court said the exemption for documents compiled for 
law enforcement purposes does not apply in this case because the 
letters were not originally obtained or generated for law 
enforcement purposes 
today the supreme court said the appeals court was wrong about 
the exemptions scope 
documents having been compiled once for the purpose of routine 
audits wer not disqualified from being compiled again later for a 
different purpose justice harry a blackmun wrote for the court 
we do not accept the distinction the court of appeals drew 
between documents that originally were assembled for law 
enforcement purposes and those that were not so originally 
assembled he said 
blackmun said soughtafter documents may fall under the foia 
exemption if they have been gathered or stored by a law enforcement 
agency when the response to the foia request must be made 
blackmuns opinion was joined by chief justice william h 
rehnquist and justices william j brennan byron r white sandra 
day oconnor and anthony m kennedy 
justices john paul stevens antonin scalia and thurgood marshall 
dissented 
the case is john doe agency vs john doe corp 881083 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

