<TEXT>
the remains of a revolutionary priest are to be 
enshrined tuesday in the hallowed pantheon in a bicentennial 
ceremony that has revived 200yearold grievances of the roman 
catholic church against the french revolution 
church leaders are boycotting the event the last planned in a 
bicentennial year in which the archbishop of paris says we were 
invited to commemorate a period when the church was violently 
persecuted 
henri gregoire better known as the abbe gregoire fought 
slavery proposed the abolition of the monarchy and backed a 
controversial oath of allegiance to the state that clergy were 
forced to take 
to close out a year of bicentennial parades exhibits and 
fireworks president francois mitterrand decided to honor the abbe 
gregoire and two other revolutionary figures the philosopher 
condorcet and the mathematician gaspard monge 
a solemn ceremony is planned tuesday evening for the placing of 
their remains in the pantheon a disaffected church in the form of 
a classical temple on the left bank where the french republic 
honors its heroes 
frances roman catholic hierarchy decided not to send any 
representatives although papal nuncio lorenzo antonetti will 
represent pope john paul ii at the ceremony 
the church in france while no longer the antirepublican force 
it once was has not forgotten the revolutions massacres of clergy 
and violent desecration of churches 
the abbe gregoire was a central figure in the drama that split 
the revolution and the church the 1790 civil constitution of the 
clergy which required the clergy to swear allegiance to the state 
many resisted maintaining their loyalty to the pope and relations 
rapidly deteriorated 
the abbe gregoire defended a conception of the church which 
differs from the catholic tradition cardinal jeanmarie 
lustiger the archbishop of paris was quoted as saying in an 
interview in le monde in which he explained the decision not to 
attend the ceremony 
but lustiger said he would preside at an office for the dead to 
mark the abbe gregoires exhumation from montparnasse cemetery 
even though his predecessor as archbishop of paris refused to 
authorize a church funeral when gregoire died in 1831 
the papal nuncios presence confirms the desire of the holy 
see to help france and french catholics heal the wounds which may 
remain from the revolutionary crisis and the antireligious 
violence early in this century lustiger was quoted as saying 
lustiger said he considered it worthwhile to honor the abbe 
gregoire because of his struggle for the emancipation of the 
jews for the rights of blacks and the abolition of slavery 
but he also said the french bishops had tried to maintain their 
proper role with dignity throughout the bicentennial 
celebrations in which we were invited to commemorate a period 
when the church was violently persecuted 
the french hierarchys decision not to participate in the 
ceremony for the abbe gregoire has been questioned discreetly by 
other church leaders 
the absence of bishops at the pantheon will surprise a certain 
number of christians i understand that reaction said monsignor 
jacques delaporte the bishop of cambrai 
the others being honored tuesday are less controversial 
jeanantoine caritat marquis de condorcet a friend of voltaire 
and other philosophes opposed the death penalty and favored 
equal rights for women during the jacobin purge of the girondins 
he was arrested and died in prison in march 1794 in his case the 
transfer of remains is symbolic his body was thrown in a common 
grave and never recovered 
gaspard monge the inventor of descriptive geometry served on 
the revolutionary committee that developed the metric system he 
gave courses in manufacture of cannons and powder for the defense 
of the young republic and later was close to napoleon losing all 
his honors when napoleon fell in 1814 
</TEXT>
