<TEXT>
an air force delta 2 propelled a 
military navigation satellite into orbit today to join a network of 
spacecraft which tell us and allied military forces where they 
are within 50 feet anywhere in the world 
the 128foot booster blazed away from its launch pad at 110 
pm after being postponed one day because of a problem with a fuel 
tank pressurization system the problem was corrected overnight 
a very smooth flight the rocket is right on track said air 
force lt col ron rand the launch commentator as the delta 2 
climbed toward orbit 
twentyfive minutes after liftoff rand reported the satellite 
had separated and was in a proper orbit ranging out to 11000 miles 
high everything appears to have gone very well with the 
flight he said 
the payload is a 65 million navstar satellite whose signals are 
designed to guide military units such as planes ships submarines 
tanks and land forces with pinpoint accuracy 
four similar satellites all launched from here earlier this 
year are orbiting earth as part of a global navigation network 
the military launch was given priority over another rocket whose 
flight was postponed last week in that case the liftoff of a 
commercial titan 3 rocket carrying a pair of foreign communications 
satellites was delayed thursday night by a computer software 
problem and again friday by stormy weather 
that launch now rescheduled for dec 20 will be martin 
mariettas first commercial one for paying customers 
