<TEXT>
former white house aide lyn nofziger won a 
legal victory monday when the supreme court refused to reinstate 
his 1988 illegal lobbying conviction 
that kind of news is always welcome it certainly makes the 
holiday season a bit brighter said nofzigers lawyer lawrence 
barcella 
the justices without comment let stand a federal appeals court 
ruling that overturned nofzigers conviction on charges he 
illegally lobbied top presidential aides within a year of leaving 
the reagan administration 
barcella said dropping any further prosecution of nofziger 
represents the only humane course but independent counsel 
james mckay declined comment saying he would have an announcement 
at some future date 
nofziger was white house political director from 1981 when 
president reagan took office until early 1982 
he was convicted of lobbying on behalf of three private clients 
the scandalplagued wedtech corp a maritime workers union and 
fairchild corp he was sentenced to 90 days in jail and fined 
30000 
prosecutors said nofziger lobbied for an army engine contract 
for wedtech for the placement of civilian sailors on navy vessels 
and for continued air force purchases of an antitank aircraft made 
by fairchild 
he was tried under the ethics in government act of 1978 which 
imposes a oneyear ban on lobbying former colleagues after a person 
leaves service in the federal governments executive branch 
the ban covered lobbying on any matter in which the lobbyists 
former agency has a direct and substantial interest 
nofziger contended he did not violate the law because he was 
trying to stimulate not influence or exploit white house interest 
on issues of concern to his clients 
the us circuit court of appeals here ruled june 27 that 
nozigers criminal indictment should have been dismissed because it 
did not charge him with having knowingly lobbied on matters in 
which white house officials possessed a direct and substantial 
interest 
in his appeal independent counsel mckay said the appeals court 
ruling hampers congress attempt to deal with the spectacle of 
highlevel government officials using the revolving door to turn 
their government service into lucrative lobbying businesses when 
the ink had barely dried on their resignations 
requiring prosecutors to prove a former government employee knew 
the subject of his lobbying was of direct and substantial 
interest to his former agency will reward purposeful ignorance or 
heedlessness mckay argued 
lawyers for nofziger said the appeals court ruling is unlikely 
to have any future impact because of legislation enacted by 
congress in november 
the legislation the ethics reform act of 1989 eliminates the 
direct and substantial interest requirement to create a flat 
ban on government employees lobbying their former agencies within a 
year of their resignations 
</TEXT>
