<TEXT>
sequoia and kings canyon 
national parks which adjoin each other in the sierra are the 
first to resume a policy of letting some lightning fires burn 
themselves out officials said monday 
a national park service policy to let selected fires burn 
naturally was suspended last year following criticism over letting 
wildfires get out of control in yellowstone national park 
the suspension has been lifted only at sequoia and kings canyon 
following approval by regional director lew albert of a revised 
fire management plan for the parks 200 miles north of los angeles 
said spokesman william tweed 
based on an environmental assessment albert found that resuming 
the policy would have no signficant environmental impact 
fires will be allowed to burn only within specific ranges of 
temperature wind speed and fuel moisture tweed said enough 
firefighters must be on hand to put a fire out if necessary 
the goal of the program is to perpetuate the role of natural 
fire in park ecosystems without threatening public safety or 
property tweed said in a statement 
