homelessness aids and crack cocaine are 
overwhelming child welfare services nationwide and are contributing 
to a growing number of children in foster care a congressional 
report said monday 
the report issued by the democratic majority on the house select 
committee on children youth and families said federal funding for 
major childrens services especially those designed to keep 
children in their homes has not kept pace with the problem 
this is ronald reagans legacy to the 1990s rep george 
miller dcalif committee chairman said at a news conference 
this was the prescription for the 1980s and its been a complete 
disaster 
social workers cannot keep up with huge caseloads and children 
are being placed on waiting lists rather than given services he 
said 
it means we are devastating hundreds of thousands of children 
these children are becoming candidates for longterm dependency 
on our social welfare system miller said were really talking 
here about he candidates school for future penetentiary 
residents 
the report estimates that the number of children placed in 
foster care juvenile detention centers and mental health 
facilities has grown to nearly 500000 and could reach 840000 by 
1995 
the report said its survey of 11 large states showed the number 
of children in foster care dropped by 9 percent between 1980 and 
1985 however the number rose 23 percent between 1985 and 1988 
while federal funding for child welfare services aimed at keeping 
children in their homes rose 7 percent according to the report 
the number of children in public and private juvenile detention 
centers rose 27 percent from 1979 to 1987 as funding under the 
juvenile justice and delinquency prevention act declined from 100 
million in fiscal 1979 to 667 million in fiscal 1989 the report 
said 
the number of children in mental health facilities soared 60 
percent between 1983 and 1986 the report said federal block 
grants for mental health services provided 503 million to the 
states in fiscal 1989 17 million less than the sum of programs 
consolidated into block grants in 1981 it said 
the states surveyed were california florida illinois 
michigan missouri new jersey new york north carolina ohio 
pennsylvania and texas 
among the reasons cited for the increases in foster placements 
and detentions was drug and alcohol abuse the number of babies 
born drugexposed reached 375000 in 1988 a number that has 
quadrupled in the last three years the report said 
it also said reports of abused or neglected children rose 82 
percent to 22 million between 1981 and 1988 also requests for 
shelter for homeless families rose 18 percent from 1987 to 1988 
said the report citing a us conference of mayors report 
republicans on the committee disputed the democrats projection 
that outofhome placements for children will jump 73 percent over 
the next five years they took issue with the reports methods of 
calculating the projection and basing it on an 11state survey 
our concern is that the numbers are so unreliable that the 
message will be dismissed their statement said 
the dissenters said more nationwide information is needed on 
adoption and foster care and they blamed the states for some of 
the problems in the system four different general accounting 
office reports have shown states have failed to implement 
procedures and protections established by the federal government to 
protect children they said 
