some details of the plan were spelled out for an energy 
department advisory panel by david b van leuven who will be 
associate general manager for defense programs at rocky flats when 
egampg inc takes over as plant operator jan 1 
the current operator rockwell international corp announced in 
september it was quitting rocky flats because of a dispute with the 
energy department over potential criminal liability for past 
environmental violations 
the plant on the outskirts of denver is owned by the energy 
department and is the nations only maker of plutonium triggers for 
nuclear weapons 
a phased halt to rocky flats plutonium operations began in 
midnovember to give egampg time to develop an improvement plan the 
plant has been criticized by government and independent inspectors 
for a wide variety of shortcomings including inadequate safeguards 
against worker exposure to radiation 
van leuven told the advisory committee on nuclear facility 
safety that he would inspect the management of all six plutonium 
buildings in the next few weeks and that he would bring five 
executives from other egampgoperated facilities to be on ready 
standby to replace up to five of the building managers 
van leuven said he already had determined that five of the six 
managers who work for rockwell international are unlikely to meet 
egampgs managerial standards 
one has the capabilities im looking for the rest are 
questionable he said 
