michigan colleges and universities should develop 
a zero tolerance policy and require a course in ethnic 
relations to improve campus race relations the michigan civil 
rights commission recommended monday 
the recommendations stemmed from the commissions discussions 
with administrators students and faculty from the university of 
michigan and michigan state ferris state and western michigan 
universities 
it is our hope that universities will look at these 
recommendations as a guide and use them to implement a program of 
this sort on their campus commission chairman benny napoleon 
said at a commission meeting 
racial tensions rose on several campuses this year sitins were 
held at ferris state michigan state and wayne state universities 
students demanded racial sensitivity from staff and other students 
and policies against individuals who commit racist acts 
the zero tolerance policy would define unlawful and 
unacceptable acts of racism and authorize punishments 
the ethnicrelations class would be required for all freshman to 
sensitize individuals to racial issues and concerns at least seven 
us universities already require such a class 
an official at one michigan institution said he didnt believe a 
course would solve the racial problems 
i believe race relations should be spread around in all 
courses not stuffed into one western michigan president diether 
h haenicke said 
napoleon said some michigan schools already are implementing 
programs 
msu is scheduled to begin its ethnicrelations class in 
1992 he said we would hope that they would begin earlier than 
that 
university of michigan president james duderstadt told the 
economic club of grand rapids on monday that all universities have 
a responsibility to strive for ethnic diversification because the 
united states will become increasingly multicultural in the next 
century 
he said he believes his school has made remarkable progress 
in reducing racial tension through minority recruiting 
the recommendations also included setting up procedures to 
process discrimination complaints developing and distributing a 
booklet for students on their civil rights and periodic reviews of 
campus policies and their success 
through a concerted effort we can develop programs that not 
only reduce current tension but also prevent future unlawful acts 
of harassment from occurring state department of civil rights 
director john roy castillo said 
