the navy plans to drop a smallscale model of 
a satellite launch vehicle into californias monterey bay on 
thursday in a hushhush program to develop a reusable lowcost 
rocket a space industry newspaper said monday 
the test will involve releasing the model booster from a 
helicopter to demonstrate that the booster can survive a water 
landing at 200 mph said space news citing unnamed sources 
the navy was asked for comment but did not immediately respond 
the only reusable space vehicles the united states has are the 
shuttle and its rocket boosters the shuttle lands on a runway the 
boosters drop into the ocean are towed back to port to be 
refurbished for reuse 
the project is being conducted on a shoestring budget with 
navy funds authorized by navy admiral carlisle trost chief of 
naval operations according to the navy source space news said 
in its dec 11 preview issue 
the rocket would take off from the ocean surface which would 
provide tremendous flexibility in launching secret missions the 
spent stages would be slowed in their fall and buoyed at the 
surface by balloons 
