after four years of disagreements the 
international monetary fund announced monday it has reached an 
accord with peru that could mean financial aid for the country if 
peruvian policies meet its approval 
an official of the fund who spoke on condition he not be named 
said peru had made a payment of 423 million the 800 million it 
owes the fund the payment covers only the arrears since september 
of this year 
peru has been in trouble with lenders since president alan 
garcia was elected in 1985 and announced that he would make only 
partial payments of interest on the countrys debts at that time 
peru owed 14 billion abroad now the figure is closer to 20 
billion 
its financial troubles have been worsened by the continuing 
rebellion of a strong leftist group the shining path and a 
thriving traffic in drugs 
owned by 152 governments the fund negotiates at length with 
those in financial trouble it gives its help only when the 
borrowing government agrees on a set of policies it approves 
usually these include cuts in government spending especially on 
official payrolls and subsidies and often a devaluation of the 
countrys currency 
peru is one of 10 countries with a total arrears of 35 billion 
to the fund and so ineligible for more finanical aid from it and 
in practice unlikely to get much from anyone else this year the 
fund started a series of what it called shadow programs under 
which governments promised new policies but got no immediate money 
vietnam guayana zambia somalia and now peru have started such 
programs 
if the fund finds they are doing well after a year or so they 
will start getting its financial help 
