<TEXT>
two moslem leaders in britain agree salman rushdie 
blasphemed their religion in his book the satanic verses but 
they differ sharply on what to do about it 
one noted moslem figure hesham elessawy said he wanted to go 
to iran and win a reprieve for the author but after a tehran 
newspaper said the hanging rope awaited him he stayed in 
england 
a prominent moslem kalim siddiqui supports the death sentence 
imposed on rushdie by the late iranian leader ayatollah ruhollah 
khomeini and thinks rushdie should be hounded perpetually until 
his book published 14 months ago is withdrawn from bookshelves 
rushdie a bombayborn moslem has been in hiding under police 
guard since feb 14 khomeini died in iran on june 3 but his edict 
endures 
siddiqui director of the moslem institute says khomeinis 
edict is unchallengeable and that rushdie got nothing less than 
he thoroughly deserved 
but while favoring the death decree absolutely he says it 
is not for moslems living in this country to break british law to 
bring rushdie to book 
elessawy chairman of the islamic society for the promotion of 
religious tolerance contends that the death sentence contradicts 
the korans teachings 
as a moslem i should really suppress the human response and 
adopt the religious response which is dont punish him leave 
him to god to punish or forgive him as he wishes elessawy said 
in an interview 
he planned a lecture tour of iran egypt and the persian gulf 
states in february to dispute khomeinis edict but canceled it when 
iran declined to guarantee his safety and its semiofficial 
newspaper kehan warned he would be hanged 
the death sentence is really a slur is something that defames 
the religion of islam elessawy maintained 
as long as the man stays in hiding well stand accused of 
putting him there and keeping him there well be regarded as 
potential killers 
elessawy said he hoped at least to remove the 52million 
bounty offered by iranian clerics for rushdies assassination by 
designating it the tactics of gangsters and not worthy of the 
islamic republic 
elessawy and siddiqui have never met elessawys group seeks 
to identify and correct causes of intolerance toward moslems 
siddiquis disseminates information on moslem political thought 
siddiqui came to britain from pakistan in 1954 elessawy came 
from egypt in 1970 both are married with three children and both 
are thoroughly westernized in appearance they share an easy humor 
and a mutual contempt 
in a booklined study at his house in suburban london siddiqui 
58 dismissed elessawy as an apologist 
totally idiotic the man is to put it mildly he said 
elessawy 43 seated in his ornamented dentists office in 
harley st londons medical row said siddiquis speeches verge on 
incitement to murder but dont let me be the judge 
in october at a moslem rally in northern england siddiqui 
called for a show of hands on whether the death sentence was just 
and virtually all 250 people in the audience were reported to have 
raised their hands a bbctv poll published the previous night 
indicated only 35 percent of britains 2 million moslems were in 
favor of the death penalty 
police are investigating whether siddiqui was guilty of 
incitement and have obtained a court order forcing the bbc to hand 
over its footage of the rally 
siddiqui complains the british media portray him as a sort of 
rabble rouser the opposite to salman rushdie as it were 
he says moslems have no choice but to protest and show that 
anyone who tries to go down the same road as mr rushdie in the 
future will be dealt with much more severely 
siddiqui wants rushdie and his publishers viking penguin to 
withdraw the book and that profits from the 12 million copies sold 
should be shared among relatives of 26 people who died in 
antirushdie riots in india and pakistan 
they should make amends and then well call it a day 
siddiqui said otherwise this is going to be an issue in 50 
years from now 
elessawy said there is not one single moslem who is not 
angered by the book but he thinks rushdie might defuse the furor 
by affixing labels to his book making clear the contents are 
fictional 
he said he met rushdie on a train two weeks before the author 
was driven into hiding and suggested the disclaimer label but 
rushdie rejected it as tantamount to an apology 
rushdie is not showing any good will at all elessawy 
added in fact hes doing the opposite hes trying to promote 
the campaign against him because he wants to sell more books 
rushdie 42 continues to write and occasionally aims barbed 
comments at his opponents 
in a book review he wrote recently for the times literary 
supplement he alluded to the public burning of his book by moslems 
with this thought to burn a book is not to destroy it one 
minute of darkness will not make us blind 
