<TEXT>
while the government pursues 
racial reform on several other fronts rigid apartheid remains the 
rule at staterun schools despite a growing clamor for change 
for millions of black children schools are overcrowded or 
unavailable scores of white schools have closed because of pupil 
shortages yet the government recently rebuffed a coalition of 
white parents teachers and students who petitioned to establish 
south africas first multiracial public school 
amid all his encouraging moves president de klerk has just 
failed an acid test said the star the countrys largest daily 
newspaper no matter how compelling the reasons to amend that 
archaic policy no matter how desperate the pleas from those 
affected apartheid remains alive and kicking in the school 
system 
since taking office in midaugust president fw de klerk 
repeatedly has vowed to eliminate racial discrimination yet his 
support for segregated state schools is unwavering despite official 
figures indicating that the government spends nearly five times as 
much to educate a white pupil as a black one 
according to the minister in charge of white education piet 
clase school segregation is essential to ensure cultural and 
linguistic continuity between the home and the classroom 
the acid test referred to by the star was the fate of 
johannesburg girls high school a 102yearold institution the 
government targeted for closure because of declining enrollment 
a substantial majority of the teachers students and parents 
launched an unprecedented campaign to save the whitesonly school 
by opening it to children of the thousands of black mixedrace and 
indian families who have moved into the innercity neighborhood in 
defiance of residential segregation laws 
after hinting that it might allow a experimental multiracial 
public school the government decided instead on a compromise it 
would allow the high school to remain in operation but only as a 
private school 
the state will provide a subsidy of up to 45 percent of its 
operating costs but even so few of the current pupils are 
expected to able to afford the projected monthly fees of 100 rand 
38 
the school also is expected to lose two of its five grades 
because of financial constraints and will be able to cater to no 
more than 240 pupils although the facility has a capacity of 
nearly 700 
the creation of a private school is no victory as far as i am 
concerned said neil mcgurk a member of a provisional board of 
trustees for the new school the new school will have nothing to 
do with the old 
mcgurk the principal of a multiracial roman catholic school 
said the government tends to lower its subsidies to private schools 
with relatively high proportions of black pupils 
the state has a natural temptation to mobilize as much 
resources as possible for whites he said 
the government currently spends the equivalent of about 800 a 
year to educate a white child compared to less than 200 per black 
child this gap has been reduced from previous years but the 
government recently abandoned a 10year plan to equalize the 
percapita education spending 
in soweto the largest black township with an estimated 25 
million residents schools have been plagued by violence severe 
overcrowding shortages of textbooks poor performances on exams 
and deteriorating facilities 
in many soweto schools there are 40 to 50 pupils for each 
teacher 
the south african institute of race relations reported in 
november that 196 white schools have been closed in the past 10 
years and that remaining white schools have more than 250000 
vacant places an estimated 1 million black children have no 
schools to go to the institute said 
a handful of the closeddown white schools have been made 
available to the education departments for indians and mixedrace 
people but most have been leased to other government agencies and 
42 are unused said the institute an independent research 
organization 
given the crying need for school places for black pupils this 
is a criminal waste of a high order said a recent editorial in 
the star 
the campaign to integrate johannesburg girls high school has 
been emulated in other cities under the banner of a group called 
all schools for all people 
ahmed moonda a leader of the group said that if the state does 
not act a defiance campaign will be launched next year in which 
parents will take their children to the nearest school and demand 
enrollment 
we do not want to cause disruptions but we may be forced 
to he said the state is simply fostering illiteracy among our 
kids 
