<TEXT>
while foreign businessmen complain of 
obstacles to japanese markets travelers complain that crowded 
airports are the most frustrating barriers to getting into the 
country 
in hopes of easing the bottleneck for air travelers the 
japanese are building an island in osaka bay and plan to put an 
airport on it but few industry insiders think it will be the 
answer 
the project is moving smoothly along nevertheless in contrast 
to tokyos narita airport where riot police recently battled 
radicals who used firebombs to defend land on which a runway was to 
have been completed 15 years ago 
at narita eight farmers still grow vegetables on and around the 
planned second runway refusing to sell their land though police 
have begun to dismantle buildings erected by radicals supporting 
the farmers industry sources are doubtful the second runway will 
be completed by the end its new deadline two years from now 
for more than 20 years protests against narita have left six 
people dead the airport is surrounded by barbed wire and riot 
police it is not connected to key rail lines to tokyo 40 miles 
away 
the 7 billion kansai airport at osaka however will be out in 
the bay and not likely to generate any fights with the citys 
residents 
the airport is one of the worlds biggest civil engineering 
projects of the 1990s but it has its critics 
japan is famous for its bullet trains and sparkling subways but 
its links to the outside world international airports are 
widely considered unworthy of a great economic power 
the main link tokyos narita airport is becoming a symbol of 
japans closed nature says yasuo sakakibara an economics 
professor 
new tokyo international airport as narita is officially called 
greets passengers after long transpacific flights with crowds and 
confusion after picking up their luggage passengers get a choice 
between a 200 40mile taxi ride to tokyo or a wait of an hour or 
more for a bus 
narita handled 4 million more passengers last year than it was 
planned for all squeezing through the same number of immigration 
counters as when the airport opened in 1978 
with just one runway narita handles 17 million passengers a 
year new yorks john f kennedy airport with five runways 
handles 10 million 
the congestion is terrible says richard jurek director of 
pacific operations for northwest airlines the day narita 
opened it had already reached its comfortable capacity 
the new kansai airport an hours flight west of tokyo is 
supposed to relieve the problem when it opens in 1993 
but industry sources say the runway is too short the distance 
to osaka too far and its link highways too narrow an airport 
serving a metropolitan region that produces 2 percent of the 
worlds economic output needs at least three runways they say not 
just one three were originally planned and the ministry of 
transport is still hoping for them but the ministry of finance 
says the country can afford only one 
industry sources predict kansai airport will be full within a 
year or two of its opening they expect growth in japans 
international passengers in the next few years to nearly match the 
more than 20 percent annual growth since 1987 
today boats cruise in osaka bay where 747s will take off 
machines disgorge enough sand to fill scores of houston astrodomes 
into a box 27 miles long that will be the airports supposedly 
earthquakeproof base it is one of the deepest of manmade 
islands standing in 60 feet of water 
on it will rise an ultramodern terminal with people movers and 
indoor landscaping a twolevel bridge will carry trains and cars 
across 23 miles of water to osakas shore 
japan squeezes 122 million people half the population of the 
united states into a habitable area about the size of 
pennsylvania few of them want an airport in their backyard that 
keeps airports small and inconvenient to city centers the island 
airport will be an hours bus ride from downtown osaka 
the sand used for the island is costing more than it should 
because of pricefixing among contractors who were stiffly fined 
by japans antitrust agency the united states has charged that 
collusive business practices like the sand cartel keep out foreign 
businesses washington has made access to the airports 
construction by us companies a major trade issue with the 
japanese 
after long negotiations the airport opened bidding on 
construction and supplies to foreign firms and an italian 
architect won a design contest for the terminal building 
despite the prospect of problems ahead foreign airlines are 
lining up for flight slots at the new airport for many airlines 
the pacific and japan are the fastest growing and most profitable 
markets in the world 
