<TEXT>
stuck on what to buy this christmas 
make it video 
whether you want to splurge spree invest or just stuff a few 
stockings here are some wonderful items to buy and some excellent 
excuses for buying them 
splurge 
a new television set with a 27inch screen 
if youre a typical american youve been watching that 19inch 
tube for more than a few years while new technology has been making 
it obsolete 
this is no time to wait for high definition tv the best 
estimates put hdtv at least five years away from the expensive end 
of the marketplace and maybe even longer before its affordable in 
the mass consumer market 
japanese manufacturers are designing video and audio circuitry 
that tweaks the tv signal for all its worth they make enhanced 
definition with much sharper pictures even if you live in an 
area where cable tv isnt available everywhere much of the 
broadcast soundtrack in major us cities is in hifi stereo so a 
tinny little speaker just isnt going to make it for the 1990s 
an inexpensive 19inch set costs about 200 in a discount 
house its about 400 for a 19inch tv loaded with the new 
technology and about 700 for a lowend hightech 27inch tube 
in areas where such electronic goods are heavily discounted you 
can shop around and get a stunning stereophonic cableready tv 
set for less than 1000 were talking automatic tuning inputs 
for multiple video sources outputs to your home stereo a 
smart remote control and a picture thatll knock your eyes out 
go for it 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
spree 
a combination laserdisc and compact disc player 
if you havent already taken the plunge into digital audio for 
your home stereo you should compact discs dont wear out and make 
any stereo system sound startlingly better the budgetminded 
approach is to buy a small portable unit to start then trade up to 
a fullfeatured model but if youve got some christmas money to 
throw around why not get into digital audio with a machine that 
also plays videos they cost around 500 in the discount houses 
but the laserdisc image is said to be 60 percent sharper than the 
best vhs player and the sound quality is just like a cd 
newly released laserdiscs are sometimes cheaper than vhs tapes 
a vhs new release that retails for 8995 is in the video disc rack 
for 4995 and some may sell for 2995 and in theory laserdiscs 
dont wear out and the digital signal will never become obsolete 
also there are certain features you cant get with a vcr such 
as letterbox formatting that allows you to see the wide screen 
image 
in the fullfeature laserdisc format the producers include 
incredibly comprehensive supplementary material the threedisc 
package for the 1936 classic musical showboat includes excerpts 
from the 1929 universal film version excerpts of ziegfields 1932 
broadway revival interviews with stars a color film documentary 
on showboats a visual essay of 300 stills tracing the history of 
showboats and the history of the musical on stage screen and 
radio and enough other archival material to choke a librarian 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
invest 
a vhs player 
not a recorder mind you but a transportable playonly machine 
that can run off a 12volt car boat or rv system and is about half 
the size and half the cost of a videocassette recorder 
its great to have a backup when your main vcr breaks down its 
great to have a portable vcr when youre on vacation or out of the 
country you have to look for these but theyre available at most 
video dealers and start at around 150 
a fourhead hifi super vhs videocassette recorder or at 
the very least a stereo vcr that you can pipe through your home 
audio system 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
stocking stuffers 
a nonabrasive vcr head cleaner use it only when you have 
significant deterioration in picture quality tape heads are 
delicate precision devices and should not be messed with 
blank tapes people never have enough blank tapes and they 
never buy themselves high quality tapes 
videocassette storage racks people never have enough places to 
store videocassettes which need and deserve a safe dustfree 
resting place 
a years worth of cable tv service surprisingly affordable 
gift certificates are available call your local cable company for 
details 
videocassettes most people are surprisingly reluctant to buy 
themselves their favorite movies and you usually know what your 
friends and relatives enjoy from teenage mutant ninja turtles 
to rock concert videos operas and great games of the world series 
even better the emergence of big retail video chains and the 
plethora of available programming has pushed down the price of 
video software 
suprisingly the monster hits of recent years are most heavily 
discounted batman the summer megahit is couponed rebated 
and generally knocked down to less than 20 who framed roger 
rabbit lists for about 20 et the extraterrestrial is 
about 25 the right stuff lists for around 30 and the newly 
restored version of lawrence of arabia is 40 
theres also an abundance of competitively priced 
christmasoriented programming in video stores at this time of the 
year from old favorites such as irving berlins holiday inn to 
cartoons that will hose down the kids late on christmas day 
laserdiscs any great film makes for a great disc and most are 
digitally remastered to take advantage of the technology blade 
runner is a big favorite so are gone with the wind cropped 
back down to its original format and its colors restored and the 
godfather but the hit pick for christmas giving has to be 
lawrence of arabia 
the 1962 academy awardwinning film was restored from its 
original negatives under the supervision of director david lean 
who added 20 minutes of footage cut from the original release the 
standard clv 4995 and the extended play 3 discs 12495 list 
contain copious supplementary material 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
some video donts 
dont buy for video collectors without very specific knowledge 
or instruction either theyll already have it theyll quibble at 
the quality of the recording or the format or theyll say they 
only wanted ishtar any format man 
buy them a can of compressed air for blowing dust out of their 
machines or a spray bottle of glass cleaner and nolint paper 
towels buy them a videocassette rewinder batterypowered 2995 
at radio shack or a bulk eraser to get rid of unwanted recordings 
dont forget to buy instant fireplace at 995 the 
logical culmination of a television culture put the cassette in 
