<TEXT>
sculpture is risky business for french artist 
chantal cottet instead of chisels she sculpts with dynamite hand 
grenades and artillery shells 
cottet 39 is the inventor of blast art a term she created 
to describe the jagged hunks of twisted steel born from her 
carefully planned explosions 
her studio is located on her familys farm outside paris in the 
middle of corn and beet root fields stretching as far as the eye 
can see yet the explosions she sets off using between 11 and 33 
pounds of dynamite rattle windows in villages miles away 
the farm is dotted with sculpture of all shapes and sizes 
including a giant mushroom form made from an imploded gas canister 
and graceful flower pots sprouting stainless steel tulips from 
inside 
during a recent interview cottet demonstrated her art she used 
penthrite the same explosive that police say was used to bomb a 
passenger jet of the french airline uta last october over west 
africa 
the penthrite itself isnt dangerous things get risky the 
moment you connect the explosive to the detonator she said 
holding up the twoinch device if this goes off before im 
ready ill lose three fingers and an eye 
the most treacherous aspect of her work she explained comes 
from elements she cannot control such as the random electrical 
current generated by highspeed trains passing by just 164 feet 
from the woods where she does the blasting and which could in 
fact ignite the explosive before she is safely away 
preparations for the explosion took more than an hour cottet 
wrapped the plasticcoated penthrite cords in a spiral design 
around the insides of a cylindrical steel frame that supported a 
vacuumsealed aluminum can 
at one point the rusted frame tipped over with cottet inside 
and narrowly missed the water table in which the explosion was to 
take place 
once the can was secured inside the frame it was lowered into 
the vat cottet then wound up an electrical sparker that set off 
the blast 
three two one she yelled yanking the lever the loud 
blast sent a shower of water high into the air wetting onlookers 
steam rose from the churning water the frame was hoisted high 
in the air and there was cottets sculpture a dripping crumpled 
aluminum can filled with dirt balls 
but she is only halfpleased 
the hardest part of my work is trying to determine how the 
material is going to react given the amount of explosive used and 
how it is attached she said this isnt bad but i think ill 
explode it again to open up the top part 
the second explosion this time on the ground takes visitors 
watching from behind a shatterproof glass window by surprise as 
the can is propelled into the air behind a cloud of pungent smoke 
the carcass will become a finished work of art once it is washed 
and polished 
cottet has been working with explosives for seven years ever 
since the day she found an abandoned rusting gas canister a 
bunch of kids probably blew up for fun 
its hollow shape was what id been trying to achieve in marble 
and wood for a long time she said the moment i saw the can i 
knew id found my calling 
she has perfected her knowledge and use of explosives during 
frequent seminars at french military bases in the beginning she 
was the oddball artist today she is known to everyone and is 
taken seriously enough to receive grants from the culture and 
defense ministries 
besides penthrite and dynamite which she stores in special 
temperature and humiditycontrolled closets protected by 
sophisticated alarm systems cottet sculpts with hand grenades and 
artillery shells 
she finds out when the military base in bourges is planning to 
fire missiles and artillery shells and places her material in the 
right position so it will be blown up in the way she wants 
look at this piece of armored steel she said caressing the 
hundreds of jagged dents left by bullets isnt it beautiful 
not everyone agrees the artist has run into considerable 
opposition not only from art institutions such as the beaux art 
academy where she trained but also from private galleries 
collectors and even fellow artists 
people told me i was crazy when i began working with 
explosives they might look at the sculpture and say they like it 
but when they find out it was done with explosives they shy 
away she said 
but she dismissed the idea that her work is offputting because 
it bears the traces of violence and ultimately death to me the 
sculpture conveys notions of power and energy latent in the metal 
she likes being called a pioneer but is sorry she has no 
students to train 
im sure huge strides could be made in this field if there 
were more of us she said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

