<TEXT>
mary gordon is an author and a fairly popular 
one too but her mother wished she had taken a more secure job 
such as stenography 
other family members agreed the author can still remember her 
cousin a nun remarking how much she disliked her books even her 
beloved uncle criticized her work calling it dirty its never 
stopped her though 
if gordon had never produced a single novel shed still write 
perhaps keep a journal or diary or make notes to herself if 
necessary she wouldnt feel well otherwise its how she best 
expresses herself 
growing up in an irish household uncomfortable with verbal 
communiation writing was the only way she could imagine life 
outside her unhappy family 
her novels final payments men and angels and the new 
the other side 1995 viking are printed confessions 
attempts at saying the unsayable penetrations of characters who 
conceal their emotions 
irish culture does not value emotional display the author 
said in a interview so it certainly doesnt value emotional 
articulateness it values stoicism it values silence and it values 
keeping things to yourself 
i know that inarticulate people have very rich inner lives 
they just dont have the language for it some people who are 
educated or uppermiddleclass assume that if you control language 
or own language that means you have a finer inner life but you 
can speak emotionally and not be revealing any true emotions 
the imminent death of ellen mcnamara in her 90s brings 
together four generations in the other side but this family 
seems only to share unhappiness infidelities casual cruelty and 
emotional instability have made the mcnamaras incapable of 
supporting each other even at this time 
i wouldnt know what to write about a good family gordon 
said they dont interest me as a writing problem what are you 
going to say they all got together somebody took the leg of the 
chicken somebody took the breast and somebody got the wing who 
cares 
but she cant resist a streak of creeping optimism theres 
hope from dan and camille two of the mcnamara grandchildren who 
seek love outside their unhappy marraiges and darci dans playful 
daughter 
i have a lot of faith in darci shes got juice and shes got 
pizzaz life is probably not going to be as wonderful and glorious 
as she thinks it is but shes got life shes got life force 
the author said 
i think what happens to you as a child a young child is 
tremendously important i think feeling approved of feeling loved 
feeling safe is something that cant be replaced if you dont 
have that i think youre really crippled its as if you had to 
learn to walk again as an adult 
gordons characters are weighted down by guilt a belief that 
all earthly pleasure is undeserved an exaggerated sense of duty 
in final payments a young woman shuts herself off from the 
outside world for years to nurse her sick father the housekeeper 
in men and angels takes it upon herself to save her boss 
from the sins of humanity 
obligation drives vincent mcnamara ellens husband to leave 
the nursing home where he had finally found happiness to fulfill a 
longforgotten promise to be at his wifes side when she dies 
the question of what do you owe people and what you allow for 
yourself is very vexing and i think the irish are very 
idealistic gordon said they love the possibility of martyrdom 
looming somewhere in the future 
they love the idea of a heroic goal that you can devote your 
life to i think its shaped their political life and its shaped 
their literature 
gordon a native of long island wrote poetry until age 25 and 
then started on final payments which came out in 1978 she 
takes her characters through sickness and health faith and 
despair sex and religion vulnerability the dependance on 
uncontrollable forces fascinates gordon and terrorizes her as 
well 
the uncomplicated joy of darci is shadowed by ellen a once 
formidable woman reduced to desperate howls of pain 
one of the terrible things about aging is the way that you 
lived does not matter nearly so much as the way youre going to 
die she said you can live a really rich noble life and die 
like a jibbering animal you can live like a total jerk and have a 
nothing life but have a rather beautiful peaceful death 
words beaten into sound thats what happens to ellen as she 
nears death gordons characters struggle between language and 
emotion and for most of their lives language wins but in the 
end emotion resurfaces as a writer gordon tries to weave them 
together 
the rhythm of words and the physical existence of words is 
very important to me i write very physically to get the intensity 
of emotional experience into intensely connected language is a 
very very big goal 
i think theres always a problem with language what does 
langauge actually reveal the distance between what we want to say 
and what we are able to say is tragically great 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

