<TEXT>
a bookkeeping issue that seemingly only an 
accountant could love is commanding keen interest on capitol hill 
the debate on how to tally the budget deficit could have big 
implications for social security 
the deficit by law is defined as the difference between federal 
income and spending including the billions earned and spent for 
social security benefits so as the social security trust funds 
build big reserves to help pay for baby boomers retirement in the 
next century the official deficit tally is held down by payroll 
and employer taxes earmarked for social security benefits 
democrats and republicans both are increasingly supporting 
taking social securitys moneymaking trust funds out of the 
deficit equation claiming that the current system masks the extent 
of the rest of the governments red ink 
in fiscal 1988 for example the governments 155 billion 
deficit would have been 194 billion if social security were 
excluded in 1989 the official deficit fell to 152 billion 
without social security it was 2045 billion 
we are playing a game with the way we report the budget 
deficit each year sen john heinz told colleagues in october 
it seems to me it is time to fess up to what we are doing and do 
something about it 
heinz rpa held up action on an urgent debt bill until 
congressional leaders agreed to tackle the deficitdefinition issue 
early next year 
those who favor removing social security from the equation say 
the unrealistically rosy budget picture removes pressure to cut the 
deficit and that the move would help protect the trust fund 
reserves 
what were trying to do is stop the looting of that trust 
fund and get truth in budgeting said sen ernest hollings 
dsc 
if we can save our social security trust fund surpluses 
rather than spending them on government consumption as we do 
presently we can more than double our net national savings rate 
said sen daniel patrick moynihan dny 
critics maintain that removing social security from the equation 
would excuse a big chunk of the budget about 20 percent of 
federal spending from making more contributions toward reducing 
the deficit they also say that once trust funds no longer are 
counted politicians might spend the reserves on pet projects or 
bigger benefits for todays retirees at the expense of tomorrows 
every day i and other members of the ways and means committee 
answer mail asking for benefit expansions by stating that we cannot 
further improve benefits because of the budget deficit rep dan 
rostenkowski dill told a house panel recently this argument 
will be eliminated when social security becomes completely 
offbudget 
robert d reischauer director of the congressional budget 
office shares that concern it certainly would be harder to fend 
off proposals to raise benefits or cut payroll taxes without the 
discipline of deficit reduction reischauer told lawmakers 
for example he said congress might have been unable to resist 
recent efforts to boost payments to notch babies americans 
born in 1917 through 1921 who get lower benefits due to a change 
in the method of calculation 
social security commissioner gwendolyn king calls the 
deficitdefinition debate one of the most specious discussions 
youre ever going to find in government since it shifts numbers 
on paper without altering spending 
yet she is wary of tinkering with the system i have a real 
concern if taking it offbudget means making it more vulnerable to 
pull it out there have got to be some safeguards built around that 
trust fund to ensure that nobody can raid it 
rostenkowski believes social security is better off left as it 
is but he has introduced legislation to help protect the trust 
funds if they are removed from the deficit calculations under the 
bill a house member could object to any legislation that increased 
social security benefits without providing for a corresponding 
increase in revenues such an objection could be overruled only by 
a majority vote in the house rules committee or by 60 votes in the 
senate 
without such protections rostenkowski said congress may not 
have the political courage to say no to those proposals which 
would increase benefits immediately but at the same time further 
jeopardize our childrens benefits 
mrs king called rostenkowskis bill a step in the right 
direction but said it wasnt strong enough to adequately protect 
the trust funds 
accompanying the deficitdefinition debate is the broader 
question of whether social security should continue stockpiling 
money now to meet the big retirement demands of the baby boom 
generation 
the general accounting office early in 1989 said congress should 
consider rolling back payroll tax increases because the social 
security reserves are being used to finance the current 
operations of the government and are masking the size of the 
onbudget deficit 
returning social security to a payasyougo system would 
involve reducing payroll taxes in the 1990s and raising them above 
scheduled levels in the next century when benefit costs will rise 
as the baby boomers retire 
this would eliminate the illusory buildup of reserves that now 
represents little more than a mechanism for using the payroll tax 
to finance the general operations of government the gao said 
</TEXT>
