<TEXT>
consumers bingedin the 1980s indulging 
themselves with everything from fancy gourmet foods to electronic 
gadgets and luxury vacations 
now on the cusp of a new decade consumers bloated with debt 
are sobering up 
the us marketplace bore the full weight of the postwar baby 
boom during the 80s many grownup boomers ignored the example set 
by thrifty parents and spent liberally helping to fuel the longest 
peacetime economic expansion in american history 
they were helped in their pursuit of consumer happiness by some 
fortuitous economic events 
inflation was tamed in the early part of the decade by the 
federal reserves tight money policies and the prime lending rate 
which had peaked at 215 percent in december 1980 fell closer to 
10 percent by late 1982 
a big income tax cut was engineered by president reagan a bull 
market on wall street kicked up piles of money for lucky investors 
a strong dollar made imported goods like japanese electronics and 
german automobiles the standards by which all good consuming 
americans were measured 
people went shopping like crazy we were on a spending binge 
in the 1980s said sandra shaber an economist with the futures 
group in washington for most of the decade americans were spared 
the pair of miseries that plagued the 1970s and early 80s rampant 
food and fuel inflation 
advertising jingles proclaiming you deserve a break today or 
asking cheekily who says you cant have it all summarized the 
spendthrift mentality of yuppies the buzzword for young urban 
professionals 
they were not into postponed gratification said 
floridabased consultant carol farmer 
yuppies embodied 80sstyle conspicuous consumption although 
representing less than an estimated 5 percent of the 76 million 
americans born between 1946 and 64 they were the vanguard of the 
babyboom generation setting trends in consumer behavior 
more consumers than ever before were armed with credit cards and 
carried the buynow paylater concept to the limit 
over 606 million charge cards of all kinds including ones 
offered by retailers were held by americans at the end of 1988 up 
from 380 million in 1979 according to figures compiled by the 
bankcard holders of america a nonprofit group 
leo j shapiro whose chicagobased market research firm tracks 
trends said shopping habits changed drastically during the decade 
dualincome families had no room for chief shoppers whose main 
mission in life is keeping cupboards from going bare and keeping 
house 
the result was more individuals shopping for themselves giving 
rise to specialty retailers each supplying specific types of 
merchandise these niche merchants are expected to thrive in the 
90s shapiro said 
trend spotter faith popcorn of the marketing consulting firm 
brain reserve inc said consumers seemed obsessed with props during 
the 80s things that made them look good or helped project a 
certain image 
the principal consequence of all this spending was an 
accumulation of debt and an accompanying decline in savings 
the savings rate measured as a percentage of spendable personal 
income sank to some unusually low depths in the 80s 32 percent 
in 1987 compared with an average between 65 percent and 7 percent 
in the three prior decades 
the economy in general looks a lot different than it did when 
the boom began the tax cut left behind a big budget deficit the 
flood of imports threw the trade balance out of whack inflation 
spurred along by aggressive spending poses a new threat 
against the backdrop of impending hard times consumer tastes 
are beginning to change shifting away from extravagance toward 
practicality the experts believe 
furniture not fast cars and home computers not glitzy 
trinkets will be the peoples choice of the 90s with a larger 
share of babyboomers coping with the responsibility and expense of 
child rearing purchases will be more sensible predicts ms 
popcorn the marketing consultant 
the 1980s were for show and the 1990s are for go in terms of 
where is it going to get me in the future ms popcorn said 
shapiro thinks of it as a shift away from abundance toward the 
precious which he describes as an intense enjoyment of the 
things you have rather than simple gluttony 
even if belts are tightened a few notches consumers will remain 
a driving force of economic activity but their power may be 
channeled in different directions or diminished as the economy 
matures and sorts out imbalances particularly in foreign trade 
in the 1980s we were consuming more than we produced at 
home ms shaber said final demand in the united states was 
greater than domestic production to close the gap we have to do 
the reverse 
</TEXT>
