<TEXT>
the money decade of the 1980s brought both heady 
success and egregious excess to wall street 
the securities markets returned the favor by taking a hand in 
setting the economic and political course of the decade for 
american society 
stock traders celebrated the ascendance of deregulation 
technology and global investing with a historic bull market that 
began in the summer of 1982 and reached new highs as late as the 
autumn of 1989 
it has been a very unusual bull market the longest we have 
ever had in peacetime said raymond f devoe jr a veteran 
analyst at the firm of legg mason wood walker inc 
it outlasted several prominent participants who by the end of 
the decade were serving prison terms or banished from the business 
for their parts in a series of scandals 
in the ultimate test of its staying power the bull market 
survived the worst market drop in more than half a century the 
crash of 1987 that culminated in black monday on oct 19 of that 
year 
wall street in the 80s was unfailingly controversial as well 
while the bull market signaled a sevenyear period of economic 
expansion that was welcomed by many business managers and 
consumers it was assailed by social critics as the emblem of an 
age of materialism 
many wall streeters themselves decried the new computerized 
trading techniques it helped spawn strategies like index 
arbitrage and portfolio insurance that collectively came under the 
label program trading 
worst of all said some the boom on wall street was financed in 
large part by a mountain of debt that might someday collapse with 
devastating consequences 
still with all their blemishes the 1980s lived up to their 
billing on the street as the decade of financial assets 
gone were the bouts of rapid inflation and rapidly rising 
interest rates that depressed paper investments in the 1970s 
elevating in their place tangible assets such as gold and 
collectibles 
stocks and bonds were back in favor as a way to participate in 
the growth and resilience of the american economy 
as they recovered their strength the stock and bond markets 
flexed their muscles playing a newly prominent role in the shaping 
of government policies affecting the economy 
at the beginning of the 1980s it was the bond markets turn to 
play vigilante acting as a kind of selfappointed surrogate 
for the federal reserve by increasing interest rates each time its 
traders sensed a new stirring of inflation 
by the time of the 1987 crash the stock market also had emerged 
as a vigilante force impelling central bankers to ease up on 
credit conditions whenever it felt the threat of recession 
the new breed of financial vigilante was quick to strike 
sending the dow jones average of 30 industrials down a record 508 
points on black monday in 1987 and administering another 190point 
beating nearly two years later on oct 13 1989 
despite those rude interruptions the net results for the decade 
showed emphatic advances the dow jones industrials which started 
the 1980s at 83874 hovered near 2700 in the waning weeks of the 
decade 
that kind of performance wont be easy to match in the 1990s 
for the average to triple again it would have to climb past 8000 
some observers see reason to hope for more good news the 
nations labor force is likely to grow more slowly in the 1990s 
putting pressure on business to invest in greater amounts of 
productivityenhancing equipment says richard peterson chief 
economist at chicagos continental bank 
the net effect of increasing investment in business equipment 
will be a pattern of steady economic expansion through the 1990s 
peterson asserts 
nevertheless many analysts wonder whether more unpleasant 
shocks await a generation that grew up with the image of wall 
street as inexhaustible horn of plenty 
as devoe put it an awful lot of people are being seduced to 
the idea that were never going to have another bear market again 
</TEXT>
