to those who received mbas in 1981 wall street 
beckoned like a sirens song 
although a recession gripped the nation the securities industry 
and investment banks were on their way to reshaping american 
businesses and they were hiring legions of fresh mbas to do the 
job 
takeovers restructurings and stock and bond offerings became 
fortunemaking vehicles for an army of young people tales of 
23yearolds with 300000 salaries plus bonuses abounded and lured 
flocks of people to the nations business schools 
but what a difference a decade makes 
these days new yorks financial district is quiet and 
depressed tens of thousands of people were let go following the 
oct 19 1987 market collapse the stock markets unsettling 
volatility this fall has hurt new hiring plans 
no new people are coming into the securities industry said 
susan perkins an 81 new york university mba grad and vice 
president at the investment research boutique of gerard klauer 
mattison amp co 
lucrative fees from megadeals withered this year as the dollar 
volume of takeovers slumped 28 percent from 1988s heady pace 
according to securities data corp investment houses have scaled 
back commissions and shut entire departments to save money some 
estimate bonuses will be trimmed by as much as 30 percent this year 
the big salaries that deal people commanded during 80s were 
clearly out of line and they still are said randall rochman a 
