<TEXT>
it was almost unimaginable the wests 
most prominent banker jetting to moscow to advise the archenemy of 
capitalism 
but federal reserve chairman alan greenspan recently made such a 
trip a sign of the extraordinary changes that marked the 80s 
overseas 
it was a decade marked by the pursuit of a formula for economic 
success a drive that brought about wrenching changes the big 
winners were the most modern complex and open economies far down 
on the list were those dependent on natural resources and those 
with closed controlled systems 
in eastern europe some countries took their first halting 
steps toward westernstyle economies and integration into the world 
economy 
in western europe the european community finally took seriously 
its decision to fashion a single market of the dozen nations by 
1992 
the organization of petroleum exporting countries went on a 
rollercoaster ride that carried oil prices to wild levels before 
crashing and finally recovering 
africa was caught up in the foreign debt crisis that swept the 
worlds developing nations in the early 1980s sapping their 
economic strength and impoverishing their growing populations even 
more 
in europe the events that captured the imagination that seemed 
least likely at the start of the decade stemmed from the soviets 
tacit acknowledgement that their economic system had failed 
soviet leader mikhail gorbachev who came to power in march 
1985 pressed his perestroika program to restructure the backward 
economy trying to wrench it from centrally planned ways to a more 
marketoriented system 
there was talk of price reform and private enterprise more 
consumer goods and fewer government subsidies 
there can be no return to the old style of economic 
management asserted vladimir shemiatenkov moscows envoy to the 
european community 
but gorbachevs task remains staggering inflation is high and 
so is the governments budget deficit millions have been thrown 
out of work by the modernization efforts workers strike and 
consumers grumble 
they dont have a decent economic reform program yet said 
jan vanous of planecon a washington forecasting firm 
despite the daunting challenge reform fever is spreading in 
eastern europe particularly hungary long a leader of economic 
reform in the communist bloc and poland where the new solidarity 
leadership plans to move swiftly to a market economy 
east germany once one of the most conservative members of the 
