<TEXT>
it isnt a pleasant subject to face around 
christmas but it is appropriate to the season the subject is trash 
americans generate mountains of the stuff particularly around 
this time of year but they dont like to face the consequences 
they like it to disappear from their property and they dont like 
to think about it thereafter 
they must like to throw things away 35 pounds a day compared 
with 27 pounds a day per person in 1960 according to the 
environmental protection agency but they dont like to dwell on 
the fact that there is no away 
trash must go into recycling programs wastetoenergy 
facilities that burn it or into landfills the epa estimates 85 
percent of it goes into landfills which are filling up and closing 
down all over the country 
over the past 10 years according to an authority on the 
subject more than half the 18500 landfills that existed in 1979 
have closed and the epa now forecasts that by the 1990s only 4000 
will remain open 
conclusion much as they like to avoid it americans must face 
the issue of trash production trash collection and trash disposal 
lynn scarletts study might help already the study by scarlett 
research director of the reason foundation a conservative think 
tank based in santa monica calif has stirred interest in the 
industry and among policymakers 
the study points out four basic options available 
1 waste reduction policies 
2 recycling programs 
3 wastetoenery facilites that burn trash 
4 identification and construction of additional landfills 
scarlett observes that other industrialized nations already 
produce far less trash per person than the united states amply 
illustrating that it is possible through altered habits to 
generate less trash 
the japanese scarlett states produce only 76 percent the 
amount of garbage generated per person in the united states france 
produces even less about 60 percent and germany only 40 percent 
of american waste per person 
recycling efficiency also can be improved according to the 
study which concludes that waste hauled to landfills could be 
reduced 25 percent existing programs however handle less than 20 
percent of waste in their communities 
in fact what is referred to as recycling sometimes isnt much 
of what it earmarked for recycling merely ends up in the disposal 
site after all because in some cases the market for recycled 
products is depressed 
why asked a reason foundation spokesman should forests be 
harvested when the market for recycled newsprint might be falling 
in price his point the recycling of some items might 
simultaneously help conserve national assets 
the study states that experience with wastetoenery facilites 
produces the most dramatic results since incinerators are capable 
of handling up to 90 percent of the waste stream leaving only the 
inert ashes for disposal 
scarlett recommends all four strategies and that people be made 
aware of the costs involved which sometimes are hidden in general 
real estate taxes that customers be charged on a volume basis and 
that competition be invited from private garbage collectors and 
disposal services 
the study available at no charge to community officials 2716 
ocean park blvd santa monica calif 90405 cites seattles 
recycling program as a model that works and provides specifics on 
costs and savings in that city 
</TEXT>
